,Recommended,504370,25681903,"Posted: 24 September, 2016",all,PrimaGoosa,"*** Long Review, apologies in advance.  TL;DR - I'm so happy it's back and in good form.  ***When I saw they were releasing a BLC clone, I was skeptical at first.  I already had to watch one of my favorite games die once, and I really didn't want to watch it happen again.After playing a slew of matches today, I'm incredibly impressed with how they improved (in my opinion) on the formula.* All champions unlocked.  I feel like this is crucial for new MOBAs these days, and I feel like going with a Hearthstone-esque implementation of reward is really going to help.  It sucks being limited to 4 of 16 champions and feeling gated behind a paywall.  Now you have everything available, and you can dump money into chests for cosmetics if you want.  Now cosmetics are random, but I feel like that's OK.EDIT - I'm not 100% sure this is how the game will be when it's F2P, and if it is, I hope they have a paid package that is just the same roughly $20 for all champions unlocked forever.  I really don't like champion gating, though I also come from DOTA, so it's a foreign and unwanted concept.* Daily quests for chests.  I don't know, maybe it's just me, but I love this sort of thing on queued games.  It gives you a reason to experiment with other champions, giving you something to work toward and play the game without fussing over only rating, or some stat-based progression.* The Battlerites.  Even though I seem to always choose the same ones, that's probably just because I have a specific playstyle.  I love the little flavor these add to the game.* Simplified Roles:  Support, Melee, Ranged.  No more tank, no more healer.  Support has a heal, but it's on a cooldown instead of being spammable.  In my opinion, this means they have to be more clutch, less spam.* You face where your mouse points, not where you are WASDing.  I don't know if there's back attack modifiers in this game, but this just feels a lot cleaner.  Maybe it made the game more professional before, but I like this change.* Arena design.  Maybe I'm forgetting, but I feel like old BLC arenas were mostly open area, with maybe a couple LoS opportunities in one or two of them on the sides.  Battlerite feels, by and large, like a smaller central area with more juking potential, which is good because you often want to be interacting with that environment.  Which brings me to* Environment interaction.  Receiving additional benefits when capitalizing on positioning feels really good, and I think adds to the flow of the game.* Cracking the energy ball to receive the boost.  I like the strategy this adds to a fight, since you don't just run in and get free energy.  You can make big plays off of a team you know is going to huddle as soon as it pops (which might not be the best players on the team, but you won't always be in top tier gaming).* Health/energy pickups around the arena.  I haven't programmed myself to look for these yet, but with the reduced amount of spammed healing available, these really help you sustain if you pay attention.  Gives it a bit more of an FPS arena feel, and I really like that.* Performance.  This game runs smoothly (on low, mind you) on my 4 year old gaming laptop.  It can't run most games these days, but it can run Battlerite, and that makes me incredibly happy.Cons?  I hate only showering a game with praise, but I haven't seen any balance issues of yet.  Part of that is because I don't fully know all of the new nuances of each champion, and I'm not going to jump to conclusions.  Everything has felt manageable so far as long as I don't waste my toolset.  If I die, I often did something dumb.  If I'm out of position, again, I misplayed.It's almost exactly what I wanted out of a BLC reboot.  Plays incredibly smoothly, feels great, insanely fun.  And *somehow*, I have yet to run into a poor attitude. Everyone has been nice so far.  Maybe it's the thrill of having this sort of game back in the mix, but I've made some doozie mistakes, and still when I'm like ""Sorry about that"", it's ""np"".  And if you don't want to hear a tirade, you can completely disable chat.I thought of a con:* No scenarios.  I lived for BLC scenarios back when people queued for them.  The additional objectives made it feel more engaging for me than just an arena brawler, but I understand that they are refining their focus this time around.  If Scenarios are released in the future, I'm going to scream like a school girl at a One Direction concert.  If not, this game is still incredible.If you loved BLC, pick up this game right now.If you stopped playing BLC because of the progression garbage added to the game and the money grab that is champion pool availability lottery, pick up this game because there is none of that (and I hope that stays, even for newly released champions).If you have no idea what BLC is but you are hesitant because of DOTA and LoL, keep an eye on this game.  Watch some videos, read more reviews, and understand that it is not those games.  No 60 minutes slow downhill farming loss.  No intense vitriol for minutes on end because everyone is stuck in a losing scenario and can't get out.  You play games that are often just 5+ minutes long, and if there's frustration, odds are you won't see that person again anyway.Great game.  Love that it's back."
,Recommended,504370,25608982,"Posted: 20 September, 2016",all,Brannock,"THIS GAME IS NOT A DOTALIKE.Top-down arena battler. Fast-paced, but still deliberative: to really do well you have to keep track of opponents' cooldowns as well as your own, along with managing distance and zoning. It's more like a fighting game, really. Fully skill-based, there's no grinding or stat customization or any of that garbage. You pick your champion, you know exactly what it'll do, how much, and for how long. You can choose one battlerite (basically talents) per round in a match to adjust to the compositions of your team/enemy's team.With 2v2 and 3v3 modes, you can easily split up your groups and no one will be left out. The game is free of ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t, you just boot it up and go straight into a match, no garbage to wade through before the ""real game"" begins. Graphics are slightly cartoonish, but are very clear and it's very easy to understand what's going on. When a champion is using a channeled ability or is under a duration, the name of the ability/effect is spelled out in clear text above the model.The game is somewhat poorly optimized at time of writing this (early access) but that's improving. The chat interface, especially outside a match, is terrible and needs a lot of improvement.THIS GAME IS NOT A DOTALIKE."
