,Recommended,504370,32859280,Posted: 27 June,all,NEQSIS,"What is Battlerite?Battlerite is a hybrid somewhere between Dota 2 and World of Warcraft style Battlegrounds - you take on opponents in 2v2 and 3v3 arena-style skirmishes and try to be the last team standing (after a best of 5 match).  From Dota 2 it borrows maticulous hero balance, movement/camera mechanics, and a handful of thought-out abilities for each playable character.  From WoW Battlegrounds it borrows a focus on pure PvP; there are no objectives here other than defeat your opponent.  What is unique to Battlerite is the major importance of movement; I've found quick reaction time and mobility to be one of the most necessary skills to succeed here in order to dodge enemy attacks, zone enemy teams/players, and land powerful abilities.GameplayGameplay is fast, fluid, and has an incredibly high skill ceiling that rewards practice, hero/ability knowledge, and mechanical ability.  The devs are constantly tweaking, balancing, and updating this game which has consistently received excellent support.Dev Support / Early AccessBattlerite is currently (as of June 27, 2017) an Early Access title, but don't let that deter you. Battlerite is one of the most well-developed and supported games I've ever played in early access and I'm often highly critical of the early access model.  Note that, while the game is available for purchase during early access, it will be free when it hits release.  You hear ""free-to-play"" and immediately have fears of ""pay-to-win""? You (probably) don't. While the exact model of the F2P release are somewhat unclear, at worst, it will function like League of Legends; starting with a limited pool of champions requiring you to either play (or pay) to unlock more, and any other purchases being cosmetics. Note that any Early Access purchasers will have all current and future champions unlocked.Verdict:Idefinitely recommend, 7.5/10anyone with interest in this game (or players of Dota 2 or WoW Battlegrounds) to pick it up when it goes free upon release.  If the game seems like something you're particularly interested in, it's worth the $20 non-sale price; but on sale (or when free to play) its an even better buy.  My only major concern with the title, in addition to some questions about the F2P model, is the small player-base. While you won't have trouble finding games quickly you'll an average 3,000 players online at a time and see repeat players often.  Hopefully more will be playing when it goes free!"
