76561198066109691,Not Recommended,504370,29133907,Posted: 8 January,all,Exouds,"I found Battlerite's seemingly greatest strength to also be its greatest weakness.There are features in Battlerite that may or may not be lacking, such as the variety and value of cosmetics or the number of champions in the game's roster. Whether or not there are issues with these features and if they are important or not is up to each player to decide. Let's therefore put them aside for now.Battlerite's gameplay is very appealing. It's fairly fast, reactions from your character are almost immediate and there is no luck involved in the damage your attacks will do. Ultimately, what will decide the outcome of combat is your mastery of every facet of Battlerite's gameplay compared to your opponents. However, although the above both sounds and plays well for what might be a long time, it is eventually replaced by something hollow.Truth be told, Battlerite is a very unrewarding experience. You play your best and attempt to master the avenues for skill that the game provides you with. But those avenues are not deep enough. More importantly, they are not very satisfying to improve at. Many (but not all) issues stem from the central gameplay tenet of cooldown management. Every character has one attack ability with no cooldown alongside 8 other abilities that either do have a cooldown or are restricted in their use by a limited resource. This means that choosing when to use these gated abilities becomes of utmost importance in order to win a match.What tends to happen is a game of cooldown skill trading. I use an ability to either escape, do damage or control my opponent somehow. In response, the enemy player will do the same. We now both lack an ability, but because we both desire to gain an advantage we will use another pair of abilities. And another. This exchange keeps going until both players have exhausted all options but to hit each other with their non-cooldown based attacks. As a gated ability once again becomes available, the chain of skill trading resumes.There is indeed a good amount of things for the player to learn in this area. Managing to gain a small edge over your opponent due to better choice of abilities to use or coordinating with your ally to avoid enemy abilities without having to use one of your own are two examples. But it is not very gratifying. It is not enough to keep a firm grip of your interest. The reasons for this are several, but the most egregious one is that the game does not easily allow you to play better than your opponent without the use of cooldown restricted abilities. A combination of not easily being able to evade your opponents attacks and being unable to deal meaningful damage lies behind this.Due to space restrictions I have only been able to cover one aspect of gameplay in this review, but it is perhaps the most important one to consider. Battlerite does indeed require skill and intelligence to play well, but the reward you recieve in exchange for the time you spend is not fulfilling. The things the game ask of you are not satisfying enough to master - playing around them is not as enjoyable as it should be."
