,Recommended,504370,26261714,"Posted: 28 October, 2016",all,MaxxtoN,"MOBAS - The games that I've loved to hate in the past.TLDR Version: An excellent game for those who find regular MOBA games to be frustrating and boring.In depth review:The ground concept of a MOBA game has always been very appealing to me, a team-based competitive game that requires co-ordination and co-operation in order to achieve victory. I've played various MOBAS such as HoN/LoL and DOTA 2 but they never managed to keep my interest for very long? The reasons? Extended time of farming required before the real action starts, an early mess-up can turn the match into a complete stomp just a few minutes into the match if you died at the hands of a strong hero and horribly long matchtimes to name a few.That is why Battlerite feels like the perfect MOBA to me, even though it's technically not a MOBA but whatever. The fact that you do not need to farm or purchase items was what caught my interest at first and I decided to try it out. The controls are vastly different from your regular MOBA since your character is controlled as if you were playing a top-down shooter, like Crimsonland for example. But it works and makes for some interesting movement mechanics! I'm also a huge fan of the fact that your damage relies on consistently hitting skillshots and that there's no RNG involved (no crits or other BS like that). Matches are usually about 5-10 minutes long, making it the perfect lenght for me. The game isn't played in a traditional 5vs5 format either, you can play either 2vs2 or 3vs3, making it a lot easier to find enough friends to play with.Battlerite to me is the essence of what makes a MOBA fun. It's easy to learn, hard to master and packed to the brim with action that rewards skill over reliance on items or a particular skill-build. In short, all the good parts of a MOBA compressed into a visually appealing package that is sure to keep me entertained for a long time!"
,Recommended,504370,25613483,"Posted: 20 September, 2016",all,Ardipithecus Ramidus,You can finish a full game of Battlerite before pick/ban phase even starts.All skillshots. No RNG. No BS.
,Recommended,504370,25712403,"Posted: 26 September, 2016",all,nick,The PVP aspect of a MOBA or RPG without the MOBA and RPG. It's fun and none of the elements really felt random. I recommend it for people looking for that aspect of a game.
,Recommended,504370,25607325,"Posted: 20 September, 2016",all,Nazar,"This is not a MOBA.You do not farm creeps, you do not buy items, you do not gain levels, you do not level up skills. Instead you fight.This game is kind of in it's own genre along with it's precursor Bloodline Champions. It's a top down view fighting game where near every ability is a skillshot, and man is it fun. Everyone is on an equal level. There are no talent trees or runes. You pick a hero and play a best of 5 in 2v2 or 3v3 against an enemy team. That's not to say there's no customization. Every round you get to choose a ""Battlerite"". Battlerites are bonuses or modifiers to your abilities. Getting focused a lot in an early round? Take some defensive battlerites and counter the enemy. Everyone can see what Battlerites were chosen so it's all clearly communicated.If you're looking at this game and thinking ""Oh, I already have hundrers of dollars in DotA or LoL skins, I don't want to play *another* MOBA"" plese consider my words. This is not a MOBA. It plays nothing like those games. It is further away from a MOBA than something like Smash is from Street Fighter."
76561198043837399,Recommended,504370,26098314,"Posted: 18 October, 2016",all,gb,"Teamfighting in all its glory. There's no ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t RNG, no need to farm endlessly for gear, no need to deal with any annoying MOBA-like strategies such as split pushing etc. Just pure PvP.Champions are very well made, with a variaty of skills and mechanics.Game isn't formulaic either like most. It's not always about focusing the healer. There's a very high skill cap just of knowing the game before even fighting, which isn't obvious in a game that is in general pretty small."
