,Recommended,504370,25670216,"Posted: 24 September, 2016",all,Suttles,"Pick a hero and fight in an arena against other players.  That's the main premise of Battlerite, and while that might not sound that exciting the game's core mechanics and balance is well done.You pick a hero (15 total at the moment), choose 3v3 or 2v2, and jump almost instantly into a game.  At the start of each round you pick a Battlerite (which is a buff for your abilities that lasts in each concurrent round).  You spawn on the left side of the arena and head straight to the middle and fight over middle control. Each game is a bo5, and each round doesn't last too long.  Games are quick so it's easy to fix and understand your mistakes.The mechanics of Battlerite are neat, and play like a fighting game. You have energy and health, and as you get hit you lose some of your max health.  Poking is very important in Battlerite.  In the middle of the arena is an orb which when burst open gives energy and some lost max health back. Energy is used for your ultimate (which cost 100%), and a lesser ability that is pretty strong (which cost 25%).  Each hero also has two EX abilities, similar to a fighting game.   These 2 upgraded abilities cost a varying amount of energy and make a skill stronger. Each hero also has a mount + mount speedbost.  The mount has a small channel time, so you can use it to get around the arena and get straight into the action at the start of each round.Overall, Battlerite feels and plays like a completed game.  The game's future looks bright, and I'd gladly recommend it to anyone who enjoys PVP battles.  Even if you are casual as hell, the game offers a lot of fun and is easy to understand.   With only more content to come, it's a great purchase."
76561198004639274,Recommended,504370,25719407,"Posted: 26 September, 2016",all,Lachie,Pros:It's helping me withdraw from a crippling League of Legends addiction.Cons:I'm now horribly addicted to it.---------------------------------------------------------------10/10 would substitute life ruining addictions again.
,Recommended,504370,26074840,"Posted: 16 October, 2016",all,"Gorechili, The Most Shameful","Battlerite fills a niche that has been arguably glossed over or poorly executed since a Westwood Classic: Nox.Nox, similar to Battlerite, was a top down, fast paced, practically entirely aimed/skill based action game. The only burdens on a player were a mixture of knowledge, planning, and reflex. No errands to be done to obtain power (Gold, leveling), no lengthy time commitments (Games rarely extend longer than ten minutes), and a variety of ways to play (Multiple characters offering varied playstyles).I'm a filthy 30 something, dusty ancient without the time I once had. Battlerite lets me have the intense combat I crave, where WoW PvP, League, HOTS, and various others have strayed from due to design choice or burden of time investment. The no nonsense ""Jump in and crack skulls"" attitude is perfect for me.Plus, even though I cannot play as much as I would like, I can still tell the difference between skill levels in players fairly clearly. The gulf between a new player and an experienced one with just a single character is fantastic. Whenever I am obliterated in a game I can think ""Hey, I can do that. I wonder how he did that. Was it aiming? Skill use? Positioning? Battlerites?""The cosmetics leave a bit to be desired and don't particularly feel properly... weighted? A recolor costs a ton of the in game currency. Regardless, the Overwatch style of loot accumulation still feels great. The avatars given are a varied, quality bunch.For something that is in early access, I have hope for the game. There are plenty of characters not yet transitioned over from Bloodline Champions and I'm sure some will be completely redesigned alongside brand new characters, which gives me hope for overall diversity and freshness in the game. Plus, the built in tournament system hinted at being intergrated (similar to its presence in BLC) will be a fantastic hand up over other competitive multiplayer games currently in the market.If you want something that is new and doesn't ask you to sit down for 20+ minutes minimum while also giving you a sense of skill growth, give Battlerite a spin."
