,Recommended,504370,25692303,"Posted: 25 September, 2016",all,Sequitur,"For those that remember the ill-fated Bloodline Champions, Battlerite should already be a familiar name.From the same creators as BLC, Battlerite is a skill based (player skill, that is) arena combat game. The emphasis here is on skill shots, awareness and decision making. Presently there are 15 characters available, including ranged, support and melee classes. Each feels completely unique and comes with his own perks and weaknesses. The true beauty in this game is that no single composition feels broken, and each character is viable if played correctly.Battlerite, like BLC before it, caps maximum character health after damage has been done to them, so fights don't get drawn out endlessly - and it works marvelously. The result is powerul but not overpowered healers, that have to embrace a hybrid role by also dealing damage and crowd controlling.Before each round in a match, players get a choice of one of three battlerites - skill modifiers for character abilities. This can change the dynamic of the match significantly, as several choices alter the way a character should be played. A consequence, of course, is that no match plays exactly the same.Presently leveling up characters and completing daily quests earns you chests, which contain vanity items, such as new weapon skins, outfits and avatar portraits. I suspect this will be the main source of monetization once Battlerite goes free to play. If they follow a similar model as BLC, all characters will be able to be unlocked with in game currency.What is ultimately left is an addictive, just-one-more-match competitive PvP game that is, in its present form, already well worth the price of admission. Very highly recommended!"
