76561198040266490,Recommended,504370,30349684,Posted: 5 March,all,RazorAce,"Essentially the bane of my gaming commitment.After many years of playing BLC since Launch (Bloodline Champions, the purported prequel to Battlerite - which is not completely off the mark), one would be able to realise just how good or bad you are at the game and how much potential one has left to exploit - which is not a lot since I am not all naturally gifted at twitch-based games.Experiencing all the frustration of toxic players, tilting on ranked ladder, low player-base, lack of work being done to the game - somehow I can't help myself clicking on that icon time and time again (more true for BLC than Battlerite, but both applies).So I ask myself, why? Why do I keep coming back when I might have found, objectively, far more enjoyment from watchinglolcats.comupdate in real time?I believe the answer lies in the immediate enjoyment players are able to obtain from the game unique to the MOBA-Esque gameplay Battlerite provides and the unique depth as well as impartial ""fairness"" of the gameplay.It has the advantage of shorter games, less teamwork reliance (more possibility for carrying at a lower skill level) and twitch-based gameplay mechanics over traditional MOBAs like LoL or DOTA. When 4 or 5 players are feeding on your team, your chances of success is much lower than just 2 or even 1 player in your team being a gorilla. A part of the twitch-based gameplay mechanics means that those with good natural reflexes will largely have an advantage over those who don't, which can be justified as something to feel good about due to Darwin's theory of natural selection. This is where one would simply conclude that teamwork is really less enjoyable than playing solo, and thus the lack of reliance on teamwork before players start to become mechanically sound is a huge bonus to those frustrated being stuck with players with poor mechanics that utterly detracts from the enjoyment of the game in a competitive sense.However, I believe this game faces a huge hurdle in the time to come as it needs to one way or another increase player retention. The lack of sensible content update relative to the infrastructure BLC already has built up for Battlerite certianly does not aid their plight as typical menu content such as match history, player database (for ladder or just in general), general chat channels, detailed player stats, interactive in-game menu and various other extended features such as live observer mode are either seemingly not worked on or developed very slowly since CBT, which has been over half a year since.Which brings to the final point I'd like to address - the depth of gameplay. I came across an interesting perspective which suggested that the lack of player retention rate is due to the lack of improvement players are able to make through learning strategic information such as champion skills or map distance etc etc. I can confidently say that this is most certainly not true for the majority of the playerbase. Most players suffer from the misconception that Battlerite is by-in-large an extension of team-fights from traditional MOBAs, which to an extent, is not wrong. However, the know-how to fighting a team-fight to the absolute best of ability is completely different. In a typical lane-pushing MOBA, you have an alternative choice - to push the lane, kill minions and win the game, the ultimate goal one could objectively declare is not to kill your opponents. However, Battlerite is different, you are essentially forced to fight - either kill or be killed.Now, once players realise that, the way they play changes greatly and a lot of psychology is involved. Total health of the team becomes a thing and a huge number of instantaneous but nevertheless, well-informed decisions are required in order to obtain victory. This is where most players fall down or trip up in; they try and do things outside of their role in order to ""carry"" the game and typically would produce counter-productive results against a team with a better read on the personality or intentions than yourself and in the end, punished one way or another for doing so. An example often seen due to the ""scoreboard"" nature of the game is healers trying to deal damage. What they don't realise is, typically for every time they try to deal damage, they are missing out on a chance to heal or cc, and due to game balancing, their damage or reach are generally tweaked so that one would have to completely mechanically out-play the damage dealer in order to come out positive in trades. Not to mention that as healers take damage, they would be eventually forced into a reactive position as one would have to heal him/herself just to stay alive and consistent in total combat output (if one person dies, total output of damage and healing tilts and typically leads to loss especially if a team chooses to soft-reset). However, intuitively, players aren't easily able to accept that not all games are winnable and generally the concept that ""I have to carry the game by doing the job of two players or more"" has been thoroughly ingrained into them by that point. This only leads to a vicious cycle until some miraculous enlightenment or being taught the hard way through repetitive losses.Therefore, many players can enjoy the game for what it appears as, but subjectively looking at the player population that has tried Battlerite as a whole, not many had reached the level where they could appreciate the true depth of the game and the enjoyment derived from that.Thus, I believe it is not the depth of gameplay that needs work on by tweaking gameplay mechanics (as suggested by some players), but rather the solution lies in helping players discover the heart of the competitive gameplay which Battlerite already offers.TL;DR? - Find a better way for intermediate players to progress.Finally, despite the fact that I would recommend the game itself, I cannot, however, recommend the act of purchasing the  as SLS simply cannot convincingly justify the costs for the content they have provided so far - which is not a lot, and the ever increasingly obvious money-grabbing with mounts and cosmetics is becoming alarming when the basis of the game hinges on competitive gameplay rather than the ""casual players"" population."
