,Recommended,504370,26346314,"Posted: 31 October, 2016",all,EdoMan,"I have my gripes with this game. Although I enjoy the idea, I don't find it compelling enough for a few reasons.1.  Fighting-game-style zoning.  I find the zoning game incredibly obnoxious.  This is mainly why I don't play fighting games.  When the zoning game is too real, I end up just running in because my patience runs out.2.  Redundant skills.  I know it's probably difficult to design 20 heros with completely unique skill sets with many skills, but that's the problem... I don't feel like each character is unique enough to interest me.3.  Floaty gameplay and lack of skill feedback.  If my skills arn't properly relaying info, I begin to feel like im either missing everything or not having an impact on the match.  I'm OFTEN surprised how much damage I did in the post game stats window.. because you know.. I really didnt think any of my hits were landing.4.  Boring arena.  I'm not an mmo pvp player, therefore the arena maps with no side objectives feel boring to me.  I like to play mind games and strategy, and zoning/relying on pure mechanical skill to win are not the ways I like to win.  I know people say there are mind games in this game, but FOR ME, I feel that as long as the other person tests my patience enough, im going to end up giving htem the win just to get the match over with.5.  Graphics.  I can't pinpoint what it is as I don't really know the names of all the different styles of video game art, but It almost reminds me of diablo 3, and that is one of my all-time most hated games.  I think it ties in to the floaty gameplay, where everything looks and feels too smooth for its own good.I'm still going to recommend the game despite its subjective flaws.  I know there is a market for this type of arena game, and who am I to dissuade them from trying it out. Most people will know immediately if this game appeals to them or not. I hope that I will have a reason to revisit this game in the future as I do feel like it has potential."
