,Recommended,504370,25659140,"Posted: 23 September, 2016",all,Xanabanana,"If you're the type of dude who plays overwatch or LoL and love the high of making the occasional 1v3 play I would check this out. This game is pure unadulterated PvP action. I would not call it a moba as it has no npc's nor objectives- if anything I would compare it to Arena PvP in World of Warcraft, but with an Isometric view- also note its way faster paced, and I would say more skill based as there are very few auto-targeted abilities in this game, almost everything is a ""skillshot"" using Moba Terminology.I want to repeat, if you love making those ""Did you see that!?"" plays definitely try this game out. The game does not have a ""play of the game"" system like overwatch, but every game is recorded and allows you to cut a recording (so say you only show the part of the match where you 1v3'd) and then post it on your profile to share with friends and other players.Now, a quick mention that this is essentially an overhaul of Stunlock Studio's Previous Game, Bloodline Champions. Now that game was phenomenal, but it had several underlying issues (cough funcom cough)- this game however has addressed many of them while making it more accessable without hurting the depth of the game. I talk about these toward the bottom in the ""differences between this and BLC"" part of the review.Lets talk about how long it takes to play a match. A match plays in a best of 5 round system, with a timer at the start of the match counting down to an ""overtime"" where a painful fog circles the map to make sure slippery characters can't just stall the match out for too long- it creeps up into a small circle toward the center of the map and ~30 seconds after that it will just begin closing onto the whole map. With that being said you will usually finish a match within 10 minutes, with 20 minutes being an extreme outlier. So this pairs up against Overwatch's time to play pretty well and beats out hard Moba's for sure.The player population has only gone up since it launched, starting at 5k concurrent players on launch day and is almost at 10k concurrent players- considering how niche of a game this is thats awesome as matchmaking is actually pretty solid now that they've made sure that players in placement games aren't getting put into high rated matches. Finding a match is pretty quick- I usually get into a game within ~15 seconds and haven't waited more than 2 minutes yet.For those who have played BLC and are curious about the changes, here they are.1) Battlerites- instead of the medallion system to customize your character we have a non-grind based system that works more like Heroes of the Storm talents- at the start of each round you pick one out of three perks to add to your character- some characters have more ""clearly best/worst"" options, but for some it works very well, for example I love Bakko (Vanguard) round 1 choices are a) next auto attack deals double damage after using his leap, b) bulwark can be cancelled early to melee an opponent and apply a weaken (-50% damage/healing output) on them, or c) his short dash now Incapitates a target if they get knocked into a wall. All 3 are pretty solid options although I usually lean toward the third.2) Characters are actually talkitive- this was something I always brought up as a downside to Bloodline Champions- the characters didn't have much character outside of their appearance, in this day and age characters need to be talkative to appeal to more casual players, and hell, even as a guy who likes playing games very seriously/competitively I notice that a game that isn't very talkative doesn't seem to have the same grab on me. The voice lines are pretty limited, but its still far better than BLC was.3) Changes to general kit layout- tanks are no longer an archtype, you definitely have more beefy characters in the archtype, but tanks are no longer a full on archtype, the old tanks have been retooled to be supportive damage dealers (more emphasis on damage dealer) than in BLC. For example Rook (Glutton in BLC) lost his rock shield, eat (its now an exe ability) and his dust cloud. He instead gained a trance move that procs his attack speed buff. Also worth noting is that characters have a third ex only ability now- they changed the R button to be a move that is only useable with Ex energy (25% usually) For example Shifu's(Spearmaster) Incapitate swipe is an ex ability- although a third round perk causes it to refund its cost.What this change overall means is that its easier for new players to hop in as there's one less regular ability to keep track of its cooldown, without really removing skill cap as it means experienced players now have more options on how to use their ex energy.4) Smaller MapsThis is a big one, the maps are smaller and this helps out tremendously with keeping the game feeling fast paced. They're not ""tiny"" but the scale is definitely a bit smaller (I'd say ~20%) and there is no Bridges map, thank god.Also, for those wondering what characters are currently in, 13 of the 15 characters in game are ""ports"" of the original 16 characters in bloodlines minus Harbinger, Herald of Insight, and Thorns. I use Port lightly as they've been tweaked to fit the new battlerite system, removal of tank archtype, and addition of an ex only move. The two ""new"" characters are Pearl and Oldur, who are both supports- I don't think Herald will be coming back as Oldur is a heavily reworked Herald- but if you watched the trailer you probably noticed Seeker/Harbinger are in a mostly complete state and will probably be added soon enough.Either way, this got a bit disorganized/ranty but I would highly recommend the game, Definitely more approachable than Bloodline champions and I feel it has much more longetivity. Stunlock Studios has definitely learned from Bloodline Champions and has made a superior product."
