,Recommended,504370,25615997,"Posted: 21 September, 2016",all,Josi,"An early access game that is actually polished, smooth, and engaging. The PvP is very enjoyable, think LoL without the 20min of farming for items. You have all your abilities right off the bat and get to just jump into the game right away. Perfect game for when you only have 5-10min to play.  In my feeble experiance of 2 hours I have ran into zero issues both code wise and balance wise. Everytime I die I know what happened, why it was fault, and how I can outplay that champ/combo in the future."
,Recommended,504370,34842279,Posted: 9 September,all,daVid // PSN: Waveshaper__,"What are you looknig for?Sick of MOBAs? Sick of being locked together with unreliable teammates who are stubborn, clearly not experienced but still refusing to listen and causing you problems on top of problems? Sick of all of it when after a day of work you get home to get just 3 of these in a row in 3 matches, each lasting at least 15-20 minutes or even up to an hour depending on which game you play? You don't want to feel like you are a burden to your team because you don't have hundreds of hours in the game yet to know what to do / not to do, when, what items to get etc.?This game is inventented FOR YOU then.Despite it's looks on the videos: this is not a MOBA. The control scheme is a far more action oriented twin-stick shooter with WASD/QE/SPACE + Mouse. The whole match is one instant, giant teamfight in a 2v2 or 3v3, latter being obviously the more balanced and competitive mode. A round lasts about 2 minutes tops, first to 3 rounds won wins the match, making Battlerite an excellent game if you want to enjoy the team based action RPG elements of a MOBA, just in a far more action packed version.Playerbase, Free to Play, Early AcccessOne important thing to consider when you buy into a game like this on the current market is the playerbase. A multiplayer game can be great, but if you don't find people to play with it's worthless (see the sad case of Warhammer End Times: Vermintide). It is important to know that game is going to befree to play on launchafter Early Access, with a similar champion unlocking system League of Legends has. Being an Early Access backer grants you all the characters now and in the future for free, and a permanent exp bonus you'll share with your random teammates. Even the EA version consistently finds players real fast, so I wouldn't worry about the downtime after launch.CustomizationIt's a 1:1 copy of Overwatch with skins, weapons, victory poses and with the addition of mounts that you ride for approx. 3 seconds from the starting ring to the battle arena when a round starts. There are lootboxes, there are microtransactions for lootboxes, and 3 different currencies: one to buy champions, one to buy skins, victory poses and mounts, and one to buy the mentioned boxes that include everything above, there are no micropay only items.How does it feel?It's really good. All the animations, the controls, the pacing of the match, the clarity of knowing what's happening and who's doing what is extremely well polished, easy and fast to learn. The characters are well designed and have disctinct abilities both visually and mechanically: a one hit parry shield of a meele hero can do a lot different things on different heroes: it may trigger a berserk mode, store you a self healing charge, mirror back a projectile or allow you to dash away and heal your allies in the process. Currently there are 21 heroes with a few more expected to come for release, and while this number may seem low if you come from traditional MOBAs with their large maps and minions, itemization and whatever, this number is already very high for a simple arena game with each and every one of them earning their spot with their uniqueness, so less is more here, definitely.Is it worth the price?I have to say, no. 20 euros for this game is way too high. 15? Ehh, maybe? But around 10-12 as it has been on various sales several times, it's a fantastic deal. If you want to wait for free to play - be my guest, but that 10 bucks is worth the unlock of all content and future content."
,Recommended,504370,33704298,Posted: 21 July,all,tQby.exe,"If you like competetive games where skill is a core element, this game is for you. Battlerite has great PvP and it gives you a lot of adrenaline. Money well spent. Would recommend. 10/10!"
,Recommended,504370,25641944,"Posted: 22 September, 2016",all,John Stockton,"I've always been a firm believer that a key component to making a great game (not a good game, not a fun game, a great game) is having a solid amount of control over movement and player action. The OG game that did this was Mario 64.This game is what I like to call, ""the melee of mobas"".You have total control over your character. You move with WASD, you turn aim with your mouse. Everything is manual aiming (no click on target and auto hit). This game at its highest level is a pure demonstration of individual skill, reading your opponent, reacting to your opponnent, and teammwork (2v2 and 3v3).You'll get stomped, you'll almost get a sick 2v1 comeback and make a stupid mistake costing your team the game, and yet it still feels good.Its arena goodness without the ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t of gear. You get better - not your character."
