,Not Recommended,504370,30075484,Posted: 21 February,all,Chief,"Battlerite - Early Access ReviewIf you are currently interested in buying the game, here are some useful points about the game that may convince you (or not) to buy it. I personallywouldn'tbuy it again, mainly because of the balance and matchmaking issues, but that's me. This review was written on February 21st and everything written below is subject to change, due to the game being in Early Access.PRICE:If you buy the game now for 20€, you will get all heroes upon release. After the game is out, you'll probably have to spend more money to get them all or grind. Just for comparison, though: ARK: Survival Evolved costs about the same, so keep that in mind when you're paying for a MOBA that is actually quite shallow.You can also upgrade the 20€ game and get some cool cosmetics if you're into that. 30€ with no game copy, but I guess people still buy it for some reason. I don't think this will be available post-release. Not my cup of tea, but yeah, just so you know.GAMEPLAY, BALANCE, MATCHMAKINGThis is not a skill-based game, no matter how much people are going to try to convince you that it is. It has skill shots, but at the moment there are several issues that don't really make it based entirely on skill.Matchmaking is still in a pretty bad state, especially in 3v3 League. One example: If you play as either Ruh Kaan, Freya, Rook or Bakko (that is, if you are playing as a bit tougher melee hero), the game will far too often queue you with two damage dealers, when the enemy team will have a proper team (with a support). Still winnable, but in the current meta, supports have advantage. Thing is, the matchmaking - when there are not many people playing - starts considering you as a quasi-support, because you may have some shields or disables. Not good.In casual matchmaking you will still get queued will people in League, meaning that you're either getting stomped, especially if you're simply trying out a new champ. This may be frustrating for both ways. I personally never enjoy playing vs people who play casual, because you're literally ruining their experience by tryharding to get the rank, while all they're trying to do is relax and maybe grab a win or two versus people with the same mentality as them.Heroes are imbalanced and meta cannot be countered in any way. There areno bans, youdon't see what opponents pick so that you can react- you pick you hero and you are matched with players. Lower ranks will be fine, but on top you can be sure that more and more people will start following the meta and there's nothing you can do about it. If you will want to have fun and play with a certain hero that is not really strong, you are basically screwed. Sure, you may prove to be a better player than the guy who is playing some imbalanced trash, but he will still have advantage over you. Not saying you can't win against them, but their strength may eventually start to make you think about sacrificing fun for league progress. Also, ranged heroes rule the world.Premade league (that is, playing with teams) is in a poor state because of that. Upon reaching late plat, early diamond, people only play certain compositions in order to win. It is not a question of skill, it is a question of which heroes you pick. Want to counter them? Just play the same comp and beat them at their own game. Deep, isn't it?Competitive scene is very poor at the moment - Stunlock is trying, but meta is meta. All teams pretty much play the same in terms of how they approach the game. It's all about Varesh/Poloma/X, Croak/Jade/Lucie, Croak/Ashka/X and from time to time you may encounter Freya, Rook or Taya. There are some top players who play for fun and stick away from this, but they're a minority.3v3 was made a ""main mode"" because 30 """"""""""top players"""""""""" wrote some quasi-arguments about how much better it is - well, IT IS, imo. But do remember Stunlock listened to them because of their status, as it might happen again and you might not like it. These are largely the same people who abuse the current meta. And yes, I say abused, because that's exactly what it is if this is a skill-based game.Gameplay is really not unique and actually gets stale rather quickly. If you are a casual player, you might get bored with it rather quickly.Several heroes have very similar skills that do very similar things. At the same time, you may find it to be awesome, because there are matches where your heart will be beating like hell and the satisfaction you'll get for some of the plays may just be epic. Depends on what kind of combat you enjoy, though.Tutorial for beginners is horrible. It is one of the worst tutorials I've ever seen.Playing vs AI (also something where you may be able to test heroes and learn) mode is very bad as well. They will never challenge you in any way, and you will learn nothing.EVERYTHING ELSE (Maps, Heroes, Music, Cosmetics, Devs)Cosmetic items are bad and generic, but there's plenty. So cosmetic progression is there, but it's not a very quality progression. Again, if that is your cup of tea.Hero design is pretty generic. Nothing much to say here. A guy that looks like Death and carries a scythe, a black dude from the ""east"" that calls upon the power of the Sun, a warrior with an axe and shield, a blood-thirsty berserker, an Aussie with a boomerang, an Asian with an over-the-top sword and the typical anime haircut, a tiny evil ""thing"" that enjoys murdering stuff, a tiny kid that knows magic, a tiny person that has an obsession with fire, a sniper, a guy that goes invis, a dwarf(-looking) technician with a gun. We've seen it all before.The characters, character-wise, are not ""good"". They're stale, one-dimensional, have no history and lore. There is little-to-no story behind any of them, but for some reason, all of them originate from either South, West, East and North. Relating to them yet?Map design is generic and not really good if I'm honest. Little to no strategic gameplay. You get some from walls to run around, but not much, and getting the mid ball is all about burst, so nothing much there, really.The game has no soul apart from sometimes satisfactory gameplay. Connecting that with the points I made about heroes, there is no atmosphere. You are fighting in the arena, yet there is nothing happening. No announcer, no crowds, no cheers, no boos, nothing. Atleast there are voice actors for the heroes.Music is plain bad. It doesn't fit the high-octane action this game often delivers. It's some calm crap that makes you sleepy. Listen to Conan the Barbarian Main Theme if you'd like to see what kind of music would better suit this game:ClickMarketing and marketing decisions are poor and simply lacking, but as the same time it is wise to save the marketing money for release.The game is still in early access and has a long way to go in order to be come a good game. That being said, it is easily one of the most polished early access games currently available on Steam. Most of that is because it is so simple, but that doesn't change anything.Developers have relatively poor communication with the community, but have recently tried to improve it (and they have)Monetization is very fair at the moment, but expect it to get (a bit?/a lot?) more intrusive as the game becomes free-to-play.You can't communicate with the community while in game. Reddit is pretty much the global chat.My opinion on whether you should buy the game or not: compared to the♥♥♥♥♥♥we're facing nowadays and judging from the fact that Battlerite is still in EA, you may as well buy it. Devs' heart is on the right place, I guess. They try, but they're a long way from making a great product. Gameplay, at the moment, is fine, but that's without the frustrating imbalance and poor matchmaking."
