76561198024050562,Not Recommended,504370,28588721,"Posted: 24 December, 2016",all,Spyder,"I really wish I could give an ""neutral"" or ""average"" rating for game reviews, because I think it accurately describes this game.Battlerite is a MOBA being designed by the same people who made Bloodline Champions. The latter had an open beta in 2010 and was officially released in January of 2011. However, this was around the same time League of Legends' popularity skyrocketed. Lol's burgeoning popularity meant that Bloodline Champions was quietly swept under the rug and never heard from again.Years later, Battlerite is attempting to rekindle the good elements its predecessor had, but its future seems tenuous at best.Let's start off with the gameplay. It has a top-down, eagle-eye perspective like most MOBAs. Characters have Q, W, F, R hotkey abilities, like almost every other MOBA.Games are comprised of 2v2 and 3v3 matches. You kill the other team and get a point. After each round, you get to choose one of three ""Battlerites"" that will buff a certain ability. First team to 3 points wins.That's it. That's literally it. As of the day I type this, those are the only two game types. In Bloodline Champions, there was a deathmatch mode, a capture the flag mode, and a conquest mode where you capture certain parts of the map to win.Combat is swing and miss. You control your character with the W, A, S and D keys, and you aim with your mouse. Left mouse is your primary attack ability, and right mouse is a channeled attack. As previously mentioned, Q, E, R and F serve as your characters other abilities.Balance seems to be the biggest challenge. One patch, a character will be considered the highest tier character in the game, and the next patch they'll be nerfed into near uselessness. Some characters like Poloma and Croak are almost always used while others like Bakko and Rook are seldom seen.The game seems to have a particularly high learning curve. It's not helped by the fact that Battlerite is already hosting a notoriously toxic playerbase. It makes Dota 2 look like a tea party. (And yeah, I'm aware that every multiplayer game has angry, obnoxious manchildren. Yeah, I'm aware that you need thick skin on the Internet to endure whatever crap comes your way.) The game allows you the option to turn off chat features, but communication seems woefully vital for a game like Battlerite.Finally, you can unlock cosmetic appearances, weapons, profile pictures, mounts and victory poses; it's almost exactly like Overwatch's method. You can buy chests with gold you receive via leveling and daily quests. Alternatively, you can use real money to buy tokens which, in my opinion, cost far too much.In conclusion, I can't say that I ""hate"" the game. I think the Battlerite team is doing well for what they've made so far. But unless they want to see the fate of Bloodline Champions a second time, I think they seriously need to start looking into ways to make the game more robust. A game with nothing but 2's and 3's matches will lose its novelty quickly."
,Not Recommended,504370,32272290,Posted: 8 June,all,NecroSummoner,"This game is an absolutely fantastic game, however after almost a year there's been little changes, and we've yet to see the F2P version they have promised. The game had an amazing amount of hype, and a great community following off the bat. However, after a year of having a soon to be F2P game cost $20 it just hasn't been able to pick up the traffic and community it needs. They hardly ever come out with a new character, and seem to put their priorities into the wrong area. They should focus on getting the game complete, and pushing out the F2P version it needs, and then focus on character reworks, etc.If you're looking into getting the game because it looks cool by all means do so, it's a great game. However, keep in mind you probably won't see too many changes, updates, characters, etc. come out. It's pretty stale when it comes to new content like that."
