,Not Recommended,504370,28293797,"Posted: 10 December, 2016",all,"Pete, King of the Detectives","Battlerite falls into the same trap as many of its class-based brethren, where an initial period of excitement soon gives way to disappointment after the shiny new paint begins to peel away. The fundamental problem here is in the game's treatment of its support classes. The mere existence of a class that can heal other characters has serious implications for game balance: if the character is even somewhat viable they become a requirement for any team to succeed. Anyone who's played League will tell you about the problems that Soraka has caused, and in class-based shooters such as TF2 and Overwatch if someone doesn't man up and take on healing duty you can kiss your chances of winning goodbye. Often the problem is that these characters aren't very fun to play due to a lack of things to do other than healing, but Battlerite has the opposite problem: the healing characters are simply able to do everything. 90% of the time the person with the highest score is going to be the team's support, not only because of their healing but also because they were able to do comparable damage to the dps characters, and maybe put out the most disables too. There's simply no drawback; you don't sacrifice anything by picking a support class since they can all easily 1v1 any of the other characters in the game. It's like if the Medic had the athleticism of the Scout and the Soldier's rocket launcher, but could also airblast people just because. To give an example, here's Lucie, who has:- a middling autoattack (12 damage when the low is around 8 or 10 and the high I believe is 16)- possibly the best heal in the game (instant heal + heal over time + potential damage boost)- a massive shield (roughly 1/4th to 1/5th of a character's max health)- a knockback that also removes buffs and debuffs (and can heal)- a 3s panic (which makes you run in the opposite direction until you take a certain amount of damage AND doubles as a petrify which is similar)- a delayed poison that does two autos worth of damage- a combat roll in case she ever gets into any sort of dangerMany of the non-support characters are able to fill small niches that the supports cannot, but it never feels like you need, say, a ranged character and a tank character along with your support to win.Perhaps in a game where matches are so short including these healing classes was a mistake. I can tell you that the most fun I've had is when neither team has had a support and we can just go full retard at each other without getting constantly panicked and turned to stone. Battlerite certainly has its fair share of other balance issues, but this is the one that seems like the most off-putting to me. Obviously I got my money's worth, but I don't know how long this game is going to last if such a fundamental and obvious problem exists.(As a sidenote, Battlerite probably has the worst matchmaking in any game that I've seen; maybe it's just due to the small playerbase? It's pretty common to get rematched against the same team 2-4 times in a row, and if either team is clearly better than the other then it just isn't fun. Hopefully this gets changed somehow with the next patch, which is supposed to overhaul the entire matchmaking system.)Taster's score: C-"
