,Not Recommended,504370,25697518,"Posted: 25 September, 2016",all,Boone,"This is the first time in which I've wished I could leave just an ""OK"" review. This game does not deserve an overwhelmingly positive score, but I do not think I'd necassarily say the game isbad. I think it lies just in the middle. The game is and isn't a MOBA. By definition a MOBA is a MULTIPLAYER ONLINE BATTLE ARENA, which sums up what this game is to a tee. However, this game is more of a compilation of DotA, LoL, and HotS with many apsects of thoseFREEgames stripped away.The game very blatantly takes things from the afforementioned games, but reuses those things in a new and unique, easy-to-learn way. But perhaps the things stripped away to make this game was just too much. I feel like I'm playing just another MOBA but it's way too simple. You just go into a circle and cast abilities on each other. There is no real learning curve, no skill builds, no items... It's just learn what your characters do, and go lay the smackdown on some fools.And that's fun the first few times, but gets old really fast, especially since all of the characters are kind of just rebrands of each other. Your left mouse click is an attack. Your right click is a stronger attack that might have some casting time. Your Q is a counter attack. Your space bar is for mobilty or a shield depending on if you're playing a support or core role. Your E is generally the most diverse and unique ability. And that's that. Each of the heroes has that kind of general foundation.One thing I didn't mention though about part of the abilties is the way they handle ultimates, they give you a strong abilty and a stronger ability. Each of the abilities uses up some energy that you gain over time from either hitting things or picking stuff up around the map and you get to make the choice of whether to use your strong ability to get an advantage over the enemy, or wait for your stronger ability and win the fight that way.You might notice that I give this game points for being unique every time they do it, because I think being unique is good, but this game just isn't that unique. Like I said before, this game copies. This game even copies the bad♥♥♥♥♥♥that doesn't need to be in the game, such as loot crates. Hearthstone really started some ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t and I have had enough of it. It works for a goddamn digital card game, but now the loot crate system is in literally every ♥♥♥♥ing game and it needs to stop. IT'S TIME TO STOP. I don't need having microtransactions in your game be the norm. I don't need that to be the gimmick that keeps a game afloat. I want a game's content to be what keeps it going, not its ♥♥♥♥ing skins and that false sense of luck when you open something LEGENDARY. The♥♥♥♥♥♥is worthless and has no place being in the game. And especially not in this game in which all of the skins look exactly the same except legendaries have an epileptic glow. To me, it really feels like this game has skins just to have skins, which is exactly the thing I knew would happen right when I saw Todd Howard present his new Fallout game for iOS featuring loot crates with the same exact rarity rating from WoW.Somehow this game managed to diversify itself by adding a pricetag, putting itself on a pedastal to look down on MOBA's and say ""I'm not like you."" No, this game is just like those games, but for people looking to get the bare minimum of the MOBA experience. If this game was free, I'd probably be more inclined to give it a positive review, because it would be just another MOBA clone, but with a unique twist just unique enough to be refreshing yet nostalgic. But if this game was free, it likely would not have any recognition. It's like that old wondorous age-old question. Would you rather have Harambe live, but be forgotten, or have him killed only to be the most famous gorilla of all time?"
