,Recommended,504370,25775959,"Posted: 29 September, 2016",all,Cent,"Battlerite condenses MOBAs down to teamfights. This can be great, like a rocket league version of dota. You jump in, casual or competitive, play quick rounds with all action and no frills, no items to memorize, no hundred+ heroes to recognize. There's no RNG, no gimmicks, just the same team fights, over and over and over.Which leads to the one potential downside: It's JUST teamfights. Like a movie, even a 5 minute one, it cannot be ALL climax. There must be some build up, otherwise even the best moment lacks memorability. In the same way that losses are merely fleeting pinpricks on your ego, wins are as well.I still think Battlerite is fantastic. It accomplishes what it sets out to do with AAA polish, even in early access. I worry though, that despite having gameplay depth, it will have trouble having lasting appeal without resorting to adding new heroes every month like every other MOBA. This however, is a troublesome flaw with their design, not their execution, which is more than I can say for many games today."
